abstract: The Clevelands suffered their one hundredth defeat yesterday, being easily beaten by the Brooklyns at Washington Park. abstract: HELENA, Mon., Aug. 31. -- There is considerable excitement in Maryville, this county, over a rich strike that has been made. abstract: NEWPORT, Aug. 31. -- Golf again drew the cottagers in large numbers to the grounds of the Newport Golf Club. abstract: HARTFORD, Conn., Aug. 31. -- The feature of the day at Charter Oak Park was Star Pointer's great mile, which was in 2 minutes fiat, without slip or break, beating the track record made by the same horse last season -- 2:00 1/2. abstract: The laying of the foundations of a material temple and the upbuilding of the superstructure are two very different things. The one is a comparatively simple operation, and is quickly performed, although everything depends upon it. The other is a matter of engineering skill, careful elaboration, patient industry, and much time. It is that, moreover, upon which all eyes are fastened, while the foundation attracts but very little attention.

abstract: STOCKBRIDGE, Mass., Sept. 2. -- Markoe Robertson, Captain of the Yale Golf Club, won the Stockbridge Cup to-day over George C. Clark, Jr., ex-Captain of the Harvard Club, by one up. abstract: LITTLE ROCK, Ark., Sept. 3. -- Disastrous forest fires are raging in the southern portion of Calhoun County. abstract: What is the meaning of the term, "A Breach of the Peace "? I ask for information. Does it mean unnecessary and unseemly noise, that which annoys law-abiding citizens and disturbs the harmony of law and order? abstract: Labor Day was a lucky one for the racing firm of Bromloy  Co. With their two rather commonplace horses, Mesmerist and Previous, they managed to win both of the stakes set for decision during the afternoon, O'Connor piloting both animals to victory. abstract: There is a point that is carefully concealed from Americans in England's claims against the Boers. England demands that the South African Republic grant to Uitlanders (foreigners) naturalization and the right to vote without their forswearing allegiance to their foreign Governments. Of course, soon after being naturalized they will vote to become part of the British Empire, and, as they already outnumber the Boers three to one, the whole thing is a farce.

abstract: BURLINGTON, N.J., Sept. 7. -- Charles Diggs and his wife went away from home this morning to work. They left their four children, the eldest seven years old, and the youngest a baby, locked in their house. A fire was left in the stove. The fire grew very hot and set the house ablaze, and within a few minutes the whole structure was in flames.

abstract: RENNES, Sept. 7. -- To-day came the beginning of the end of the Dreyfus trial. With the speech of the Government Commissary. Major Carriere, the case entered upon the final stage of pleadings, and the verdict will be delivered on Monday at the latest. abstract: Returning to my club lately, I found a big office envelope containing a pile of rejected MSS. I had for a moment that peculiar feeling of the baffled and discouraged author which attacks a man who, in spite of his best endeavors, is conscious of time and labor wasted. abstract: CHICAGO, Sept. 8. -- Dr. E.M. Rosenkranz, owner of the Melrose flats, in the burning of which four people lost their lives, was arrested to-day on the order of the Coroner's Jury and lodged in jail. abstract: LONDON, Sept. 9. -- England is amazed that Dreyfus has been convicted and sentenced to ten years' imprisonment. The reason for amazement is that the retrial occupied weeks, and no evidence was offered to prove him a traitor. No case in the world was ever more thoroughly sifted. A latitude even amazing was permitted. The whole world held up its hands and said, "There was nothing like this before."

abstract: RENNES, Sept. 10. -- Dreyfus has borne the terrible shock of his reconviction with marvelous fortitude -- one might almost say with unnatural calm. Yesterday he seemed stupefied when Maitre Labori communicated to him the verdict, but he has since rallied. He passed a quiet night, and he rose when his orderly brought him water at 5 o'clock this morning just as he did during the trial, when it was necessary.

abstract: LONDON, Sept. 11. -- It would be difficult to describe adequately the indignation the verdict of the Dreyfus court-martial has evoked everywhere in England. The excitement in the Jewish quarters of London is only natural. Special prayers were offered throughout Saturday in all the synagogues on behalf of Dreyfus, and as soon as the verdict was known Jews and Jewesses were seen at every street corner, expressing execration, and many sobbing bitterly.

abstract: WILMINGTON, Del., Sept. 13. -- Several weeks ago the New York banking and brokerage firm of C.H. abstract: CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va., Sept. 13. -- The Poe Memorial Association of the University of Virginia will on Oct. 7 unveil Zolnay's bust of the poet. The day will be the fiftieth anniversary of Poe's death. Two meetings will be devoted to the occasion. In the morning Dr. C.W. abstract: CHICAGO, Sept. 16. -- A dispatch from Memphis, Tenn., says that Charles O. abstract: TACOMA, Washington, Sept. 17. -- Cold weather and absolute lack of fuel are causing an immense exodus of gold hunters from Cape Nome. abstract: SPRINGFIELD, Ill., Sept. 17. -- Gov. Tanner has ordered two companies of the Fourth Regiment, under command of Col. Bennett, to Carterville. He received a telegram this afternoon from Samuel Brush, manager of the St. Louis and Big Muddy Coal Company, at Carterville, that five of a crowd of his negro miners, who had gathered at the station, preparatory to leaving, had been killed, a mob having fired upon them.

abstract: COLUMBIA, S.C., Sept. 21. -- John Yober, a nine-year-old telegraph messenger in the little town of Newton, has become prominent in railroad circles. Mr. Heermance's term expired last Spring, and he simply held over until the other Commissioners became familiar with the routine of the commission.

abstract: LONDON, Sept. 22 -- A correspondent of The Daily Mail, who joined the Dreyfus party at Bordeaux and accompanied it to Carpentras, where the Captain now is, describes Dreyfus as "thoughtful, prematurely aged, with soft eyes, a smile like a woman's, and rather the appearance of a savant than a soldier." When told of the great wave of British sympathy in his behalf, Dreyfus wrung the correspondent's hand and showed the deepest emotion.

abstract: BRISTOL, R.I., Sept. 22. -- The sloop Columbia left her moorings in Bristol Harbor at 9 o'clock this forenoon and stood away toward Newport under mainsail and club-topsail. abstract: LEXINGTON, Ky., Sept. 23. -- The people of Kentucky now fully realize the power of the Goebel election law, under which the State election in November is to be held. abstract: In a fresh breeze from the east that only varied half a point north or south during the day, the Shamrock gave yesterday the best exhibition of sailing that she has shown since she has been in these waters. abstract: DOYLESTOWN, Penn., Sept. 24. -- The annual pilgrimage to the National Farm School, near here, took place to-day. The feature of the pilgrimage was the dedication of five new buildings. abstract: LONDON, Sept. 24. -- We are suffering from an acute spasm of military dementia, a disease to which modern empires seem peculiarly liable. abstract: MANCHESTER, Sept. 24. -- The market last week was firm and hardening, although quiet. abstract: A smoking sou' westerly gale that had been threatening for the past three days kicked up a formidable sea outside the bar at Sandy Hook yesterday, and the Shamrock remained at her mooring in the Horseshoe throughout the day. Storm signals were sent up at the life saving station early in the morning, and Capt. Patterson said that his anemometer registered a trifle more than twenty-five miles an hour.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Sept. 26. -- The financial projectors of the American Window Glass Company met here to-day and allotted the stock for the new combination. It was decided that all subscribers for stock for $10,000 or less receive the full amount, and all ever that sum are to be shaded 10 per cent. The capitalization of the company is $17,000,000, and the result of the meeting to-day indicates that the stock has been oversubscribed.

abstract: CHICAGO, Sept. 28. -- E.J. Brown, who eloped three weeks ago from Toronto with Mrs. Violet Holden, committed suicide here to-day by shooting himself because he could not bear the woman's remorse. She and her two children are penniless and are being cared for by the police. They arrived early in September and took rooms at the Continental registering as Mr. and Mrs. Holand. They soon moved to the Queen's Hotel.

abstract: Are all of Henry James's books as hopelessly bad as "The Spoils of Poynton"? abstract: In reading over your SATURDAY REVIEW article, "Where American Heraldry Is Weak," with which I agree entirely, permit me to call your attention to an error. You speak of "bar sinister" and the particular meaning of that ornament. According to my authority, which I have beside me, "Practical Heraldry," by Charles Worthy, there is no such term as "bar sinister," except misused. It is bend sinister.

abstract: In your able leading editorial article in to-day's issue of THE SATURDAY REVIEW, "Where American Heraldry Is Weak," I regret to see mention made of a "bar sinister," a term not infrequently used, as in the present instance, by those who should know that such a thing is a heraldric impossibility.
